<paragraph blockId="75.[151,1436,152,1418]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis box="[198,330,1112,1137]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Greek 
<emphasis box="[534,601,1112,1137]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">nipho</emphasis>
“snow” and Greek 
<emphasis box="[837,887,1112,1137]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">pilis</emphasis>
“hair,” referring to the whitish yellow coloration of this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="75.[151,1436,152,1418]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis box="[198,301,1192,1217]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is known only from the female. The dorsum of the body is predominantly concolorous and yellow. The yellow setae are not long and shaggy (as in 
<taxonomicName box="[929,1066,1232,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Dasymutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albiceris">
<emphasis box="[929,1066,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">D. albiceris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Tergum II has a spot of black setae anteromedially.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="75.[151,1436,152,1418]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">One specimen has the apical fringe of setae on tergum II narrowly interrupted medially with black setae. One specimen has the yellow setae on terga III and IV narrowly interrupted medially with black. In another specimen, only tergum III is narrowly interrupted medially with black setae.</paragraph>
